Data Cleaning and EDA¶

Objective:¶
  1. Discover and remedy missing values, outliers and anomalies present in dataset.
  2. Discern demarcations between nondiabetic and diabetic populations.
  3. Determine that both nondiabetic and diabetic groups are statistically signficantly different.
  4. Develop mutlivariate relationship visualizations.
  5. Deliver final cleaned dataset for SVM analysis.

Maximum and Minimum values flagged for potential outliers:

Plasma: biologically values for plasma cannot be 0, higher values (such as 199) should be addressed as outliers.

Skin: biologically values for skin mm thickness cannot be 0, higher values may be connected with a T2 diabetic comorbidity with obesity.

Insulin: biologically values for insulin cannot be 0, moreover higher values (such as 846) should be addressed as outliers.

Mass: biologically values for mass cannot be 0.

All other column variables appear to be clean.

Data Cleaning Treatment¶

excluding missing values:

Blood pressure is ~5 mm Hg lower in nondiabetics than diabetics patients (non diabetic: 70.877339 mm Hg, diabetic: 75.321429 mm Hg)

Skin thickness is ~ 6 mm lower in nondiabetics than diabetics patients (non diabetic: 27.235457 mm, diabetic: 33.000000 mm)

Insulin values are ~71 mu U/mL lower in nondiabetics than diabetic patients (non diabetic: 130.287879 mu U/mL, diabetic: 201.891473 mu U/mL)

Mass values are ~5 bmi units lower in nondiabetics than diabetic patients (non diabetic: 30.859674 (weight in kg/(height in m)^2, diabetic: 35.406767 (weight in kg/(height in m)^2)

Pedigree values are ~0.13 units lower in nondiabetics than diabetic patients (non diabetic: 0.429734, diabetic: 0.550500)

Mean value comparison between classes

excluding missing values:

Amount of pregnancies: Older woman have more children as time passes. Highest amount of pregnancies occurs in 40s age group ('40s', 7).

Plasma: Highest plasma values occur age groups 50s and 60+, indicating higher likelihood of diabetes in the groups. (('50s', 140), ('60+', 138)).

Blood pressure: As age increases, blood pressure mm Hg values increase throughout age groups 20s - 50s, and drop 4 mm Hg in 60+ (('20s', 65.34), ('50s', 79.80), ('60+', 75.81)).

Skin thickness: Highest skin thickness along the tricep measurements occur in age groups 30s and 40s. ('30s', 20.04) ('40s', 20.15)

Insulin: Highest insulin concentration values occurs in the age group 50s, indicating higher likelihood of diabetes ('50s', 109.40)

Mass: Highest bmi values occurs in the 40s-age group, suggesting obesity comorbidity with diabetes ('40s', 34.61)

Pedigree: Highest occurrence of diabetic pedigree patients occur in 50s and 30s age level (('30s', 0.5280), ('50s', 0.5289))

Disease Status: Highest proportion of diabetic class patients exist in the 40s and 50s age groups (('40s', 0.550), ('50s', 0.596))

Plasma and Insulin Varied By Disease Classification Status¶
In [61]:
sns.scatterplot(x="plas",y="insu",data=clean,hue='class',palette='GnBu_d')
Out[61]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x1a247af9b0>

Biologically insulin is a response to store glucose found in the blood plasma. Diabetics are either unresponsive to insulin due to physiological interactions derived from high fat body mass (T2 diabetes). Alternatively, the patient lost activity of the pancreatic beta islet cells and can no longer produce insulin (T1 diabetes).

In diabetic patients, we see that insulin values begin frequently at 100 and increase as high as 600. Moreover, as plasma values reach 140 and above, we see the patients are predominantly diabetic.

Final Analysis, Cleaning, and Recommendations¶

There exists an exorbitant amount of NaN values in data variable columns skin and insulin.

Since higher skin thickness is highly correlated with increased mass, there may exist multicollinearity.

Furthermore, insulin is a response to blood glucose plasma, there may exist multicollinearity as well.

Moreover, since age_level is derived from age it will undoubtedly exhibit multicollinearity.

In order to preserve total row count, data integrity, and proceed with SVM, we will take measures to remove insulin, skin and age_level from the dataset.

Remaining column variables pres, plas and mass will be imputed for median values to maintain row count.

Final dataset will contain 768 patients over 7 column variables.

In [64]:
clean = clean.drop(['insu'], axis = 1)
clean = clean.drop(['skin'], axis = 1)
clean = clean.drop(['age_level'], axis = 1)
